When to split across multiple lanes:
- Split when execution and review should be independent.
- Split when the task requires clearly different skills, evidence standards, or tools.
- Split when one person doing everything would make acceptance unreliable.
- Do not split when the work is narrow enough for one lane to complete responsibly.
- If you split, each lane should have a concrete ownership boundary and a clear output or review responsibility.

Interpret scope cues in the title and description literally. Broad wording like `everything`, `full`, `deep dive`, or repeated comma-separated facets implies broad coverage and should affect routing, decomposition, and review depth.

Coordinator objective:
- review and refine the task only if needed
- route it into concrete execution and review work
- update the project task board with real routing state
- do not complete the task just because a brief exists
- do not treat this coordinator run as the execution lane
